727546f-a.text:
Northern Boul., at the southwest corner of Bowne St., showing an old home owned by William P. Mellon in 1873.
L. Littlejohn was the owner in 1891. He, after living here a short while gave the property to the Young Men Christian Association, who demolished this house in May 1925 and erected a Y.M.C.A. thereon. One Peet, of Rogers Peet and Company lived here about 1870. This is a set of three views.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.    Views: 1   - 1922
Views: 2&3   March 1924.

727579f-a.text:
Northern Boulevard, south side, between Bowne and Union Streets, showing the Aspinwall House, probably built by John Aspinwall (about 1760), a New York merchant. It was a British
headquarters during the war for Independence.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection  About 1925

727580f-a.text:
Northern Boulevard, south side, between Union and Bowne Streets, showing the Aspinwall House, probably built by John Aspinwall (about 1760), a New York merchant, and a British headquarters in the Revolution. In 1873 the house was owned
by Darling.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection  About 1925
